<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-427-963  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 427 963.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  July 1990 v78 n7 p1176(14).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Architectural trends in military satellite communications systems.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jain, Pravin C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both military and commercial systems are currently used by theDept of Defense to meet its demand for satellite communications.andO;Current systems include the UHF Fleet Satellite Communicationssystems, which is made up of government-owned FLTSATs andleased-service from contractor-owned LEASAT satellites.andP;  FLTSATsystems supply beyond-line-of-sight communications to thetactical/mobile user community.andP;  The Airforce SatelliteCommunications System is used to disseminate emergency actionmessages to the nuclear-capable forces; the system is used bysmall ground-transportable and airborne terminals.andP;  The DefenseSatellite Communications System is used by fixed and transportableterminals and a small number of mobile terminals that supportnaval and air operations.andP;  The capacity of current systems tocommunicate with large numbers of small terminals is limited.andP;  Anew EHF (Milstar) system is scheduled to be available in the early1990s; it will be used by tactical and strategic users who needenhanced anti-jam and LPI protection.andP;  Technology must focus onhigh-gain satellite antennas with several simultaneous spot beamsand onboard signal processing to alleviate shortcomings of presentsystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsMilitaryGovernment AgencyCommunications Satellites.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartmap.andO;Caption:   DSCS II transponder and antenna configuration. (chart)DSCS III transponder and antenna configuration. (chart)Near-term MILSATCOM constellation. (map)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>